<HL>
   Money Fund Yields
   Moved Upward
   In the Latest Week
   ----
   By Georgette Jasen
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<IN>
MUTUAL AND MONEY-MARKET FUNDS (FND)
</IN>
<LP>
   Yields on money-market mutual funds turned up in the week
ended Tuesday, a delayed reaction to the uptick in short-term
interest rates of a couple of weeks ago.
   The average seven-day compound yield rose to 8% from
7.96%, the highest in more than three months, according to
IBC/Donoghue's Money Fund Report. Compound yields assume
reinvestment of dividends.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the 428 taxable funds tracked by the Holliston,
Mass.-based newsletter continued to fall, however, to $374.7
billion, their lowest point since mid-January. About $2.3
billion came out of money funds in the latest week, the
seventh consecutive weekly drop.
   Short-term interest rates have come down in the past week,
after rising for a time before that. The three-month Treasury
bill sold at Monday's auction, for instance, yielded 7.93%,
down from 8.06% the week before. But the yield on the
three-month bill was at 8.18% at the April 30 auction, up
from 8.05% the previous week.
   "We're wondering if {money fund} assets will work their
way back up again, now that rates have started to fall," said
Brenda Malizia Negus, editor of Money Fund Report. She noted
that some of the cash withdrawn from money funds in recent
weeks probably went to buy higher-yielding Treasury
securities.
   Money-fund yields typically lag behind overall interest
rate trends, as fund managers vary the maturities of their
investments to get the best possible returns. The average
maturity remained at a fairly long 44 days for the fifth
consecutive week, according to Donoghue's, indicating that
there won't be any sharp swings in money-fund yields for at
least the next few weeks. Fund investments include such
things as commercial paper (short-term corporate IOUs),
Treasury bills and bank certificates of deposit.
   The average seven-day simple yield of the taxable funds
rose to 7.70% from 7.66%. The average 30-day simple yield
remained at 7.68%, while the 30-day compound average stayed
at 7.98%.
   Yields on tax-free funds fell for the second consecutive
week. The average seven-day compound yield, for instance,
slid to 5.67% from 5.74%. That's equal to 7.88% for an
investor in the 28% tax bracket and 8.46% for someone paying
taxes at a 33% rate.
   Assets of the 221 tax-exempt funds fell by $262.3 million,
to $75.3 billion. Average maturity shortened by a day, to 41
days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900517-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900517-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   North Canadian Oils
   To Seek Full Control
   Of Its Bankeno Unit
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13
</SO>
<CO>
   NCD T.BKE
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   CALGARY, Alberta -- North Canadian Oils Ltd. said it plans
an offer to acquire the 13.5% of Bankeno Resources Ltd. that
it doesn't already own in a transaction valued at about 18
million Canadian dollars (US$15.3 million).
   If successful with its planned C$4.25-per-share offer,
North Canadian said it will merge with Bankeno. Both
companies are Calgary-based oil and gas producers.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   North Canadian said it expects to mail its offer next
week. Grant Billing, North Canadian's senior vice president,
said the company hopes to complete the purchase by June,
subject to government and regulatory approvals.
   Mr. Billing is also president of Bankeno, which said
separately that its board plans to recommend acceptance of
the offer. In Toronto Stock Exchange trading yesterday
Bankeno closed at C$4.20, up C$1.35 a share, and North
Canadian closed at C$18.125, unchanged.
   North Canadian's announcement follows its proposal Tuesday
to restructure the debt of Coseka Resources Ltd., of which it
owns 47.6%, and ultimately merge with it.
   Pending the outcome of talks with Coseka's lenders, who
collectively hold about C$165 million of debt, North Canadian
hopes also to conclude a merger with Coseka by June, said G.
Barry Padley, senior vice president, finance.
   Mr. Padley declined to offer details of the proposed
Coseka debt restructuring, or merger. But he said it would
largely involve cash. North Canadian had cash and short-term
investments of about C$250 million at the end of 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
