<HL>
   Technology &amp; Health:
   U.S. Fails to Adequately Monitor Risks
   Of Many Toxic Chemicals, Study Finds
   ----
   By Kenneth H. Bacon
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Despite growing concern about possible links
between exposure to chemicals and degenerative nerve diseases
such as Parkinson's, the U.S. fails to adequately monitor the
neurological risks of chemicals used in farms and factories,
a congressional study concludes.
   "Neurotoxic chemicals constitute a major health threat;
the social and economic consequences of excessive exposure to
them are potentially very large," warns John Gibbons, the
director of the Office of Technology Assessment, the
congressional research agency that issued the report.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The government's current system for testing chemicals and
pesticides focuses primarily on determining cancer risks. But
"adverse effects on organs and organ systems, particularly
the nervous system, may pose an equal or greater threat to
public health," the report says. "Consequently, it is
important to devise risk-assessment strategies to address
non-cancer health risks."
   The impact of toxins on the nervous system can range from
dizziness to death. Some recent scientific studies have
linked an increased incidence of two degenerative nerve
diseases -- Parkinson's and amyotrophid lateral sclerosis,
commonly known as Lou Gehrig's disease -- to environmental
factors. In addition, some researchers speculate that
prolonged exposure to some chemicals may help cause
Alzheimer's disease. But the report stresses that "no link
between a toxic chemical and the disease has been
conclusively demonstrated."
   The Environmental Protection Agency, which monitors some
65,000 toxic chemicals, is currently drafting new
neurotoxicity guidelines for pesticides. The Office of
Technology Assessment suggests a number of other steps the
government could take -- including stepped-up research
efforts and improved coordination among the EPA, the Food and
Drug Administration, the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration and other agencies that regulate pesticides,
industrial chemicals, cosmetics and pharmaceuticals.
   Increased testing for neurotoxicity could be expensive for
industry. The OTA calculates that it could boost currently
required testing costs by as much as 240%. Such increases
wouldn't have a large impact on the already high costs of
developing new drugs and pesticides, but it could
significantly boost the costs -- and therefore reduce
innovation -- of developing low-volume, specialty industrial
chemicals, the report says.
   Over the last six years, both Congress and regulatory
agencies have grown more concerned about the impact of toxins
on the nervous system. The OTA report, which is entitled
"Neurotoxicity: Identifying and Controlling Poisons of the
Nervous System," is likely to stimulate more activity in that
area. "It's time we develop new tests for neurotoxicity,
promote research into the causes and treatments of neurotoxic
effects, and use our regulatory programs to reduce human and
environmental exposure to neurotoxic chemicals," says Rep.
Robert Roe (D., N.J.), chairman of the House Committee on
Science, Space and Technology.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900517-0061
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900517-0061.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Sotheby's Art Auction Is Well-Received
   As New Sector of the Market Takes Off
   ----
   By Alexandra Peers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8
</SO>
<CO>
   BID U.CHR
</CO>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- As the impressionist art market shows signs of
cooling from its torrid pace of appreciation, another sector
of the art market may be taking off.
   Sotheby's Holdings Inc. held a well-received sale here
last night of the art collection of Lydia Winston Malbin,
which consisted mostly of Italian futurist paintings.
Moreover, the auction house had its own money on the line.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sotheby's had estimated that the artworks for sale would
fetch $56.5 million to $74.8 million. The final total for the
91 artworks sold was $74.3 million, with many of the lots
selling above their highest presale estimate.
   While the sale was technically not part of the spring
series of impressionist and modern art auctions that sets the
tone for the overall art market, it was notable because
Sotheby's had gone out on a limb to guarantee the entire
collection.
   Sotheby's declined to disclose the amount of its
guarantee, but dealers reportedly put the figure at upward of
$70 million. That includes the artworks sold last night and a
handful of others, notably a Claude Monet painting estimated
at $6 million, which are up for bid at separate Sotheby's
auctions.
   Bidding was active and broad-based from a variety of
mostly European dealers and collectors. Buyers said demand
was brisk because futurist works rarely come up for auction.
   Under a guarantee arrangement, the estate receives the
amount of the guarantee, regardless of what the bids for the
artworks total, essentially making Sotheby's, not the estate,
the primary seller. Guarantees have been much criticized
because of the conflict-of-interest questions they raise, but
they have grown increasingly common as competition for
collections has intensified among the three fine-art auction
houses here, Sotheby's, Christie's International PLC and
Habsburg, Feldman Inc.
   At the Sotheby's sale, among the top-selling artworks was
Piet Mondrian's "Composition in Black and White with Blue
Square." The stark geometric canvas sold for $6.8 million. It
had been estimated to sell for between $5 million to $7
million. Overall the handful of impressionist and modern
paintings in the Malbin collection, such as paintings by
Matisse and Miro, sold within their estimates.
   Sotheby's stock, which is traded on the New York Stock
Exchange, closed $1.25 higher at $18.625 yesterday. The stock
rose primarily on news of the stunning, world-record price
set for a Vincent van Gogh at Christie's Tuesday evening.
Kobayashi Gallery of Tokyo paid $82.5 million for "Portrait
of Dr. Gachet," almost double the previous record for an
artwork. Christie's stock also rallied in London Stock
Exchange trading, closing at #3.37 ($5.66), up 10 pence.
   At Tuesday night's impressionist painting sale at
Christie's, the total for the artworks came to about $269
million, in the midrange of the company's published presale
expectations. Overall, 24 of the 81 works Christie's
auctioned didn't sell, and of those that did, 31% sold below
their presale price estimates. Moreover at a daytime sale of
second-tier and less-expensive impressionist art yesterday,
Christie's reported that one-fourth of the artworks were
unsold.
   On balance, the results weren't as impressive as those
reached in recent years, showing a slowing in the rate of
appreciation for impressionist art, but they were better than
the doleful returns fetched for contemporary art at Sotheby's
and Christie's last week.
   Christopher Burge, president of Christie's America, noted
that, while some pieces sold below estimates on Tuesday,
"they sold," and the numbers represented a "solidifying of
the market."
   The sales so far have been a prelude to Sotheby's huge
auction of impressionist and modern paintings tonight. The
centerpiece of that sale is Pierre-Auguste Renoir's "Au
Moulin de la Galette," an ebullient, colorful depiction of a
Parisian dance hall. The estimate for the painting is $40
million to $50 million, but given the price fetched by the
more somber van Gogh, some dealers are now expecting it to
break the world record. Reportedly, the well-endowed Getty
Museum of Los Angeles is expected to be among the bidders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
