<HL>
   Bush, Congress
   Fear the Effect
   Of Deficit Cuts
   ---
   As Forecasts of Budget Gap
   Widen, Concern Grows
   About Jolt to Economy
   ----
   By David Wessel and Michel McQueen
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration's budget-deficit
projections have grown so large that concern exists in the
White House and Congress that meeting deficit targets may do
more harm than good to the economy.
   New administration forecasts show that to avoid
across-the-board spending cuts this fall, the government may
need to find as much as $64 billion in spending cuts and tax
increases -- even if the added borrowing needed to clean up
the thrift industry is excluded. If all the thrift costs are
included, as the law currently requires, they would need as
much as $114 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   At his first news conference since the start of budget
talks with Congress, President Bush said that paring the
deficit by more than 1% of the gross national product --
about $55 billion -- would "risk . . . slowing down the
economy further."
   Mr. Bush said that he won't give details of his position
on budget issues until an agreement has been reached and that
he was concerned about "frightening" the financial markets by
exaggerating the extent of the budget problem.
   The president dismissed calls by some Democrats that he
give a televised address or otherwise lead a broad public
discussion of the budget deficit, presumably to prepare the
public for the possibility of tax increases or other
measures.
   Another alternative mentioned with increasing frequency on
Capitol Hill would be to alter the targets under the
Gramm-Rudman law to require less deficit reduction this year.
Both administration and congressional negotiators already
seem prepared to alter the law so they don't have to count
the cost of the thrift bailout.
   Cutting the deficit in one year by the amount that may be
required to meet the Gramm-Rudman target might be neither
politically possible nor economically wise, some congressmen
say. "You may not be able to save that much without harming
the economy in some way," House Budget Committee Chairman
Leon Panetta (D., Calif.) warned.
   Both White House Budget Director Richard Darman and Robert
Reischauer, director of the Congressional Budget Office, are
to discuss this issue with budget negotiators this afternoon.
   A major economic rationale for trimming the federal
deficit is to curb the government's appetite for debt, thus
freeing up money for private investment and bringing down
interest rates. This, in turn, would help keep the economy
growing. But the newly expressed fear is that such a
beneficial effect might be offset by a sharp cutback in
government spending and an increase in taxes. The resulting
reduction in overall demand could slow the economy down.
   "I don't think anyone can say for sure where that line can
be drawn," Mr. Reischauer said.
   Some members of Congress say worrying about cutting too
much from the deficit is ridiculous. They say the greater
risk is that this year's deficit-reduction package, like
those in the past, will be swollen with accounting gimmicks
that have little economic impact.
   In the past several years, Congress never agreed on more
than $25 billion in real, lasting reductions of the deficit,
according to the Congressional Budget Office.
   At his news conference, Mr. Bush defended his reticence,
saying he doesn't want to "go out there and do something that
might inadvertently suggest crisis and frighten markets."
   But Democrats continued to press him. "The American people
must hear from the president about the length and breadth of
this problem, and they must also see a proposal from him,"
said Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen (D.,
Texas).
   Mr. Bush said that while he feels an obligation to be
candid with lawmakers, he sees no need to involve the public
in the discussions. Nor, he said, will he put his own
proposals out first, as some members of Congress have
suggested.
   "I want to go out when we have a bipartisan answer to the
problem, (and) say, `Here's what the problem is and here's
what the answer (is).' And if I go out there today, we don't
have a bipartisan answer, and that's the only way this
problem's going to be solved," Mr. Bush said.
   Mr. Darman now figures the deficit for the year beginning
Oct. 1, without any policy changes, will total between $123
billion and $138 billion, congressional staffers said. Mr.
Darman says thrift borrowing could add as much as $50 billion
to that total. The range is slightly different than the one
reported by lawmakers immediately after the first budget
"summit" meeting Tuesday. Under the Gramm-Rudman law, the
deficit for the year can't exceed $74 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900517-0037
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900517-0037.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Heard on the Street:
   Stripped-Down Beneficial Profits by Lending
   To the Little Guy and Shunning the Big Deals
   ----
   By David B. Hilder
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<CO>
   BNL
</CO>
<IN>
HEARD ON THE STREET (HRD)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
DIVERSIFIED FINANCIAL SERVICES, FANNIE MAE, FREDDIE MAC (FIS)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Looking for a financial services stock
untainted by commercial real estate loans, leveraged buy-out
loans, foreign loans or junk bonds? Beneficial may be a good
way to bet on the old-fashioned middle American borrower.
   After shedding unrelated businesses such as the Spiegel
mail-order catalog, Western Auto Supply and a loss-plagued
reinsurance unit, Beneficial is focused on consumer lending.
About 63% of its loans are second mortgages; most of the rest
of its assets are unsecured personal loans.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Those loans have helped Beneficial generate consistently
increasing earnings. Several analysts expect earnings to
increase about 12% this year and next; the company is widely
expected to boost its dividend 9% to a $2.40 annual rate at
its board meeting next Wednesday. Yet Beneficial shares, at
52 3/4, are selling for about 10 times trailing earnings,
while the overall market multiple is 16 times.
   Noting Beneficial's 13 consecutive quarters of increasing
earnings, analyst Sy Jacobs of Mabon Nugent says, "In an
environment where the Standard &amp; Poor's 500 earnings have
become unpredictable and disappointing, that kind of record
deserves something close to a market multiple."
   Others argue that Beneficial offers a chance to invest in
consumer lending unburdened by other businesses. Of
Beneficial's main competitors, Commercial Credit is owned by
Primerica, which has big securities and life insurance units;
and Household International has more than $2 billion of such
unpopular assets as LBO loans, commercial real estate loans
and junk bonds.
   "My theory is that Beneficial is really the only pure play
left in the consumer finance business," says Lacy M.
Shockley, a regional bank analyst with Smith Barney, a
Primerica unit.
   The major risk for Beneficial is one that the stock market
views as unlikely: A recession or depression in which
unemployment soars and middle-income borrowers stop paying
their debts.
   Over the past decade, Beneficial has increased the share
of its lending that is secured by homes, but it has remained
conservative in the amounts it will lend. Beneficial won't
allow total debt on a borrower's house to exceed 75% of its
appraised value. The amount of Beneficial's average
second-mortgage loan is $25,000; its average unsecured loan
is $2,200.
   Most Beneficial customers could get lower rates or bigger
loan amounts from banks or thrifts, but the company has
thrived by developing a network of offices staffed by
aggressive, service-oriented salespeople.
   One new program that is providing significant earnings
growth is tax-refund lending, offered through H&amp;R Block. For
a flat fee of $35, Beneficial will send a taxpayer a check
for his expected refund within a day or two after H&amp;R Block
makes an electronic tax return filing for the customer. Last
year, Beneficial made about 550,000 of the so-called "refund
anticipation loans"; this year, the number doubled to 1.1
million. Gregory Whyte, a Shearson Lehman Hutton analyst,
expects the program to contribute 65 to 70 cents a share to
earnings, up from 30 to 35 cents a share last year.
   Andrew C. Halvorsen, Beneficial's chief financial officer,
won't predict a dividend increase but says the issue "will be
a topic of discussion at the May 23 board meeting. We realize
that dividends are important to our shareholders." He also
assures investors with long memories that Beneficial doesn't
have any remaining liability for its former American
Centennial reinsurance unit. The unit, which ate up $460
million of Beneficial's capital in 1986, was sold for $10
million in cash and $98 million in notes, and its new owners
have paid Beneficial $15 million in principal and interest so
far. Mr. Halvorsen said American Centennial soon will begin
making modest payments on a $60 million note that matures in
1997 and that Beneficial carries on its books at zero.
   One drag on earnings is the Harbour Island real estate
development near Tampa, Fla., that will produce pretax losses
of about $21 million this year, which Mr. Halvorsen hopes to
reduce. A potential real estate gain literally surrounds
Beneficial's headquarters in Peapack, N.J., where the company
hopes to sell 600 acres of a 700-acre tract, now on the books
at only $11 million.
   Ms. Shockley of Smith Barney believes that within five
years, Beneficial will be acquired by a diversified financial
services company or a big regional bank. "I would not be
surprised to see a price somewhere near $100 a share," she
says.
   But beware. Beneficial's management put the company up for
sale in 1986, and some analysts estimated it could fetch a
price of $85 a share. But the best bid was only $75 a share,
which Beneficial rejected, and the stock since then hasn't
approached its takeover-induced high of 78 5/8.
   ---
   Beneficial
   (NYSE; Symbol: BNL)

   Business: Consumer lending
                                                                                                       

   Year ended Dec. 31, 1989:
   Net Income: $120.9 million; $5.01 a share
                                                                                                       

   First quarter, March 31, 1990:
   Per-share earnings: $1.37 vs. $1.13
                                                                                                       

   Average daily trading volume:
   57,251 shares
                                                                                                       

   Common shares outstanding: 22.2 million
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900517-0036
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900517-0036.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Business Brief -- Chyron Corp.:
   Net Loss of $2 Million
   Reported for Third Quarter
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B9
</SO>
<CO>
   CHY
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   Chyron Corp., a Melville, N.Y., manufacturer of television
graphics and special-effects equipment, reported a $2 million
fiscal third-quarter net loss on a 36% sales drop.
   Hurting results in the quarter were the company's halting
of a deferred-payment plan for dealers and customers,
expenses from unsuccessful merger discussions, and an
unprofitable subsidiary.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Chyron shares fell 25 cents to $1.75.
   Adjusted for a 2% stock dividend paid March 1, the loss
for the quarter ended March 31 equaled 17 cents a share,
compared with net income of $112,000, or one cent a share, in
the year-earlier period. Sales sank to $7.7 million from
$11.9 million.
   Alfred O.P. Leubert, chairman and chief executive officer,
said that effective Jan. 1, the company stopped offering
extended payment terms. Dealers now will pare inventories and
order products as they need them. "We see the loss of sales
as temporary," he said.
</TEXT>
