<HL>
   What's News --
   Business and Finance
</HL>
<DATE>
05/17/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   CONSUMER PRICES ROSE 0.2% in April, indicating retail
inflation has slowed from its rapid pace at the beginning of
the year. But many analysts said the figures suggest little
progress is being made in reducing the nation's core
inflation rate. Meanwhile, housing starts tumbled 5.8% last
month, another sign that the economy remains sluggish.
   ---
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Deficit projections by the White House have grown so large
that there is now concern that meeting Gramm-Rudman deficit
targets may do more harm than good to the economy. Bush said
paring the deficit by more than 1% of GNP would risk slowing
the economy further.
   ---
   The FAA ordered airlines to inspect pilot controls on
three models of Boeing's popular 737 jetliner. The move came
after a missing cotter pin caused a control wheel to come off
in a co-pilot's hands during a flight.
   ---
   The stock rally stalled amid uncertainty about how much
farther interest rates will decline. The Dow Jones
industrials closed off 2.77, at 2819.68, in active trading.
Long-term bonds eased, and the dollar was mixed.
   ---
   Circle K plans to revamp its product mix and pricing to
lure back former customers and attract new ones. The
convenience-store chain filed for Chapter 11 protection late
Tuesday after failing to get a pact with creditors to
restructure debt.
   ---
   A First Executive insurance unit had such a sloppy
accounting system for several years that regulators had
trouble confirming the unit's billions of dollars in
insurance reserves, New York regulators said in a report that
resulted in a recent fine.
   ---
   A major food-labeling bill moved closer to congressional
approval as a House panel brushed aside the objections of
many food-trade groups.
   ---
   Farm policy makers in Congress are rushing to pass a farm
bill before the budget summit agrees on any major cuts in
crop subsidies.
   ---
   The Big Board is expected to nominate Morgan Stanley's
chairman, S. Parker Gilbert, as vice chairman of the stock
exchange, sources said.
   ---
   Kay Jewelers' lenders appear to be losing faith in the
financially troubled jewelry retailing chain. Banks have
already pulled $16.5 million in lines of credit to the
company and would like to withdraw $32 million more.
   ---
   Western Union posted sharply wider losses and lower
revenue for the first quarter. The company has been
struggling to avoid bankruptcy.
   ---
   Landmark Land is exploring a possible sale of the company,
one week after a $967 million land sale was thwarted by
thrift regulators.
   ---
   G. Heileman Brewing filed a complaint with the U.S.
government against Canadian import restrictions against
American beer.
   ---
   Markets --
   Stocks: Volume 159,810,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials
2819.68, off 2.77; transportation 1174.08, off 3.02;
utilities 217.05, off 0.19.
   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3342.29, off
5.11.
   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 133.64, up 0.45; spot
index 135.10, up 0.15.
   Dollar: 151.67 yen, up 0.87; 1.6455 marks, off 0.0010.
